<br>
Baking:  You can make your own food.  With about 2 hours work, if that, you can get to skill 135 and make fishrolls, which last for a long, long time.  If you're in a guild that kills velious giants regularly, you get the bonus of food that lasts as long as fishrolls, but has nice stat bonuses also.  A bit higher up, there are some new recipes that last even longer, with better stats.<br>
<br>
Brewing:  Mostly useless, with one exception...the Tainted Avalanche Ale for the 9th coldain ring quest can only be made by a high-skill brewer.  Still interesting for parties or whatever, to be able to pop out a pile of drinks nobody's ever heard of.<br>
<br>
Fletching:  Definitely a good skill to pursue, at least to some extent.  With a minor amount of plat and time, you can make arrows with 150 range...great for outdoor pulling and tagging.<br>
<br>
Jewelcraft:  The most expensive skill to master, but also probably the easiest skill to turn a profit doing, assuming you have a friendly enchanter to enchant your metal.  No real use for a warrior outside the potential for profit, however.<br>
<br>
Pottery:  Crydee spoke of the *one* reason you *will* want to work on pottery.  The thurgadin gate potion.  Great for raids where getting out isn't nearly as easy as getting in, and good for getting one's self out of odd situations now and then...i.e. fell into Ldogs in velks accidentally <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Smithing:  You can make your own armor, right?  Well....kinda.  At lower levels, where 99% of smithing products are useful, you can't afford to get the skill to make them, unless you've a higher level main with decent cash flow.  The true gems here are the cultural armors..the new recipes are fabulous items, though extremely difficult to get skill for and gather items for.<br>
<br>
Tailoring:  At low levels, a little tailoring skill can help you make your own bandages...but that's about all the use I could think of concerning warriors and tailoring.  Probably the hardest tradeskill to improve, with few rewards for doing so, outside of the potential from some of the new acrylia leather recipes. <p><table width=350 height=120 border=1 style="border-color:#000000; border-width:3; border-style:solid;font-family:Arial;" cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
